<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1882-03-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1882-03-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="153" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d153">
                    <head>No. 28.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Earl <persName type="from">Granville</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Lowell</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Foreign
                                    Office</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1882-03-07"><hi rend="italic">March</hi> 7,
                            1882</date>.</dateline></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                        your letter of the 24th ultimo, forwarding a copy of a resolution of the
                        United States House of Representatives, calling for information concerning
                        the arrest and imprisonment of American citizens by the British
                        Government.</p>
                    <p>In reply, I beg leave to acquaint you that this matter has been referred to
                        the proper department of Her Majesty’s Government.</p>
                    <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>GRANVILLE.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>